For $Q4$:

Let `points[i] =` color at point `i` and `color[i] =` total color pairs of color `i`.

Let the query be of the form $[p, c]$.
$-$ Delete the color pairs formed by $(p - 1, p)$ and $(p, p + 1)$ if condition holds.
$-$ Recolor the point $p$ to color $c$.
$-$ Insert the color pairs formed by $(p - 1, p)$ and $(p, p + 1)$, if condition holds.

$O(1)$ per Query, thus $O(N)$ overall. Correct me if I'm wrong.

```
const int N = 100001 + 1;

int point[N]{}, color[N]{};

std::vector<int> colorQuery(int n, const std::vector<std::vector<int>> &queries) {
	std::fill(point, point + n + 1, 0);
	std::fill(color, color + n + 1, 0);

	std::vector<int> answer;
	for(const std::vector<int> &query: queries) {
		int p = query[0];
		int c = query[1];

		color[point[p]] -= (color[point[p - 1]] == color[point[p]]); // (p - 1, p)
		color[point[p]] -= (color[point[p]] == color[point[p + 1]]); // (p, p + 1)
		point[p] = c;
		color[point[p]] += (color[point[p - 1]] == color[point[p]]); // (p - 1, p)
		color[point[p]] += (color[point[p]] == color[point[p + 1]]); // (p, p + 1)
		answer.push_back(color[c]);
	}

	return answer;
}
```

If the question asks for total valid pairs for all colors, we can keep a variable `tot` and increment/decrement the same way as `colors[k]`.

Q4 is https://leetcode.com/problems/number-of-adjacent-elements-with-the-same-color/description/


A hashmap would be enough to solve it


```
class Solution:
    def colorTheArray(self, n: int, queries: List[List[int]]) -> List[int]:
        s = {}
        total = 0
        ans = []

        for q in queries:
            index, color = q

            # If index is not already colored
            if index not in s:
                # Check for neighbors, for each adjacent add a pair to total
                if (index - 1) in s:
                    if color == s[index - 1]:
                        total += 1
                if (index + 1) in s:
                    if color == s[index + 1]:
                        total += 1
            else:
                originalColor = s[index]

                # If its colored, we need to check if we are replacing with different color
                if originalColor != color:
                    # If adjacent neighbor had the original color then we subtract
                    # or if they have the new color, we add to the total
                    if (index - 1) in s:
                        if originalColor == s[index - 1]:
                            total -= 1
                        elif color == s[index - 1]:
                            total += 1
                    if (index + 1) in s:
                        if originalColor == s[index + 1]:
                            total -= 1
                        elif color == s[index + 1]:
                            total += 1
            s[index] = color
            ans.append(total)
        return ans
```
